Barclays, BP, Home Retail, TalkTalk: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 
2011-09-08T06:56:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-07/barclays-bp-plc-talktalk-telecom-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  Futures on the benchmark FTSE 100 Index slid less than 0.1
percent to 5,322.5 at 7:56 a.m. in  London . The FTSE 100 rose
161.75 points, or 3.1 percent, to 5,318.59 yesterday. The FTSE
All-Share Index gained 3 percent to 2,758.63, while Ireland’s
ISEQ Index advanced 2.9 percent to 2,519.42.  Barclays Plc (BARC)  : Erus Metals Ltd. was created as a
metals warehouse company, with Barclays Capital and Metalloyd
Ltd. as equal majority partners. The stock surged 6.1 percent to
159.95 pence.  BP Plc (BP/)  :  Europe ’s second-largest oil company said it
appealed against the ruling of a Russian Tyumen region court
that allowed the raid of BP’s Moscow offices on Aug. 30 and
Sept. 1. The stock jumped 4 percent to 386.5 pence.  Home Retail Group Plc (HOME)  : The company reported an
8.6 percent drop in like-for-like sales at its Argos unit in the
13 weeks ended Aug. 27 and a 3.1 percent decline at Homebase
over the same period. The shares slid 0.2 percent to 115.5
pence.  TalkTalk Telecom Group Plc (TALK)  : The U.K.’s second-
largest broadband company said it will close its operation in
Waterford, Ireland, and is entering into a 30-day consultation
period with the 575 workers based there. The shares were
unchanged at 130 pence.  William Morrison Supermarkets Plc (MRW LN): The smallest of
the U.K.’s four main supermarket chains reported an 8 percent
increase in first-half underlying pretax profit to 442 million
pounds ($705 million), beating analysts’ estimates. The shares
slid 0.7 percent to 289.4 pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
